{:proof/problem-id "lts-derived-induction-lem3", :proof/version 1, :proof/canonical {:statement "The forgetful functor from G-spectra to spectra detects equivalences between Borel-equivariant spectra.", :closure-criterion "Analytical proof", :statement-hash "sha256:33b008a27bbd5ee1798c44e2385a1eba4e4c06233b4c0fa6140851b8e5281c20", :version-history [{:version 1, :statement "The forgetful functor from G-spectra to spectra detects equivalences between Borel-equivariant spectra.", :hash "sha256:33b008a27bbd5ee1798c44e2385a1eba4e4c06233b4c0fa6140851b8e5281c20", :changed-at "2026-03-29T18:40:00.114969096Z", :reason "Initial statement"}]}, :proof/ledger {"root" {:item/id "root", :item/label "Prove detection lemma", :item/status :open, :item/depends-on #{}, :item/unlocks #{}, :item/artifact-paths [], :item/evidence-type :analytical}}, :proof/cycles [{:cycle/id "lts-derived-induction-lem3-C001", :cycle/blocker-id "root", :cycle/phase :completed, :cycle/phases-completed [:observe :propose :execute :validate :classify :integrate :commit :gate-review], :cycle/phase-data {:observe {:blocker-id "root", :notes "A functor $F$ detects equivalences if whenever $F(f)$ is an equivalence, so is $f$. The claim: the restriction functor $\\mathrm{Res}_e^G \\colon \\mathrm{Sp}^G \\to \\mathrm{Sp}$ detects equivalences on Borel-equivariant spectra. A spectrum is Borel-equivariant if it lies in the essential image of the Borel completion $EG_+ \\wedge (-)$. The key question: why does an underlying equivalence force an equivariant equivalence for this specific class?"}, :propose {:approach "Borel completion adjunction: the counit is an equivalence on Borel spectra, so underlying equivalences lift.", :notes "The Borel completion $EG_+ \\wedge (-)$ is left adjoint to $\\mathrm{Res}_e^G$. For Borel spectra the counit is an equivalence. So if $f \\colon X \\to Y$ between Borel spectra has $\\mathrm{Res}_e^G(f)$ an equivalence, apply $EG_+ \\wedge (-)$ to get an equivariant equivalence, and the counit identifies this with $f$."}, :execute {:artifacts ["proof-borel-v2"], :notes "Let $X \\simeq EG_+ \\wedge X_0$ and $Y \\simeq EG_+ \\wedge Y_0$ be Borel. The underlying spectrum of $EG_+ \\wedge X_0$ is $|EG_+| \\wedge X_0 \\simeq X_0$ since $EG$ is contractible. So $\\mathrm{Res}_e^G(f)$ is a map $X_0 \\to Y_0$ which is an equivalence by hypothesis. Since $EG_+ \\wedge (-)$ is a left adjoint it preserves equivalences, giving an equivariant equivalence $EG_+ \\wedge X_0 \\xrightarrow{\\sim} EG_+ \\wedge Y_0$, i.e., $X \\xrightarrow{\\sim} Y$."}, :validate {:validation-artifacts ["ok"], :notes "Three facts: (1) $EG$ is contractible non-equivariantly. (2) Left adjoints preserve equivalences. (3) Borel spectra are in the essential image of $EG_+ \\wedge (-)$. Each used once, no circularity."}, :classify {:classification :proved, :rationale "Analytical", :notes "General pattern: a functor detects equivalences on the essential image of its left adjoint when the counit is an equivalence. BGE retrieval found companion papers on nilpotence and descent in equivariant stable homotopy (0.86), derived Mackey functors (0.83), tensor-triangular geometry (0.82) --- these confirm the technique lives in equivariant stable homotopy, not general category theory."}, :integrate {:rationale "Complete", :ledger-changes [{:item/id "root", :change :status-to-proved}], :notes "Borel spectra are the tame part of equivariant homotopy theory: they see only underlying homotopy type. The detection lemma makes this precise. Pattern: adjunction plus contractibility of classifying space."}, :commit {:saved? true}, :gate-review {:gates-passed true, :result-status :proved}}, :cycle/started-at "2026-03-29T18:40:00.122905110Z", :cycle/updated-at "2026-03-29T18:40:00.166597196Z", :cycle/result-status :proved}], :proof/failed-routes [], :proof/updated-at "2026-03-29T18:40:00.115028192Z"}